The paper deals with structural decomposition methods, which are commonly studied in the computer science subfield of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also discusses tree decompositions and hypertree decompositions, which are topics in computational geometry (cs.CG) and data structures (cs.DS). The game-theoretic characterization of tree projections adds a dimension of theoretical computer science (cs.GT) to the paper. Finally, the algorithmic applications of the results suggest a connection to machine learning (cs.LG).
